List of Typesetting Commands                        
Formatting commands are embedded in the text. These commands are enclosed in square brackets []. Multiple commands may be entered in the same brackets if separated by either commas or semicolons.
The list of commands follows below.


[bm nÑ]           -bottom margin is set to n.
[bold] or [bd]   -turns on boldface typeface. 
[cj]             -centered justification
[fj]             -control word for filled justification
[font nÑaÑmÑeÑ] Ñ Ñ Ñ Ñ Ñ -set the font to name. Example: [font topaz]
[fsize nÑ]        -sets the font size to n. Example: [fsize 8]
[indent nÑ]       -indent this line to n spaces.
[italic] or [it] -turns on the italic attribute. Characters are
                   slanted.
[leading nÑ]      -set line leading to n.
[lj]             -command for left justification
[lm nÑ]           -sets the left margin to n.
[mag mÑ.ÑnÑ]        -magnification of m.n times the current size.
[magx mÑ.ÑnÑ]      -Horizontal magnification in the x direction only.
[magy mÑ.ÑnÑ]       -Vertical magnification in the y direction only.
[parspace nÑ]     -Paragraph spacing is set to n.
[rj]             -right justification
[rm]             -set the right margin.
[spacing nÑ]      -set line spacing to n.

~                -the tilde(~) is a special character that breaks
                  the line as soon as it encounters the tilde. 
\n               -newline
\[               -print an open bracket
\]               -print a close bracket


